      concurrently. The causes of this interference and its implications for the
      nature of attentional limitations have been controversial for 40 years,
      but recent experimental findings are beginning to provide some answers.
      Studies of the psychological refractory period effect indicate a stubborn
      bottleneck encompassing the process of choosing actions and probably
