      occipito-temporal neocortex in the cat. This deficit is classically
      ascribed to interruption of visual radiations serving cortical function
      ("cortical blindness") and is considered permanent. Return of vision to
      the hemianopic field after subsequent removal of the superior colliculus
      contralateral to the cortical lesion demonstrates that neither assumption
      is correct. The initial hemianopia is apparently due to depression of
      function of the colliculus ipsilateral to the cortical lesion, a de-
      pression maintained by influx of inhibition from the crossed colliculus.
