      trained task; however, the extent to which these benefits generalize to
      other stimuli/tasks is contentious. It has been suggested that behavioral
      decision-making/response selection training may enhance temporal visual
      attention, as measured using the attentional blink (AB) paradigm. Here, we
      show that AB can indeed be reduced through response selection training,
      which requires repeatedly performing a speeded decision-making task.
