AB  - A growing body of research suggests that dual-task interference in sensory
      consolidation (e.g., the attentional blink, AB) and response selection
      (e.g., the psychological refractory period, PRP) stems from a common
      central bottleneck of information processing. With regard to response
      selection, it is well known that training reduces dual-task interference.
      We tested whether training that is known to be effective for response
      selection can also reduce dual-task interference in sensory consolidation.
      Over two experiments, performance on a PRP paradigm (Exp. 1) and on AB
      paradigms (differing in their stimuli and task demands, Exps. 1 and 2) was
      examined after participants had completed a relevant training regimen (T1
      practice for both paradigms), an irrelevant training regimen (comparable
      sensorimotor training, not related to T1 for both tasks), a visual-search
      training regimen (Exp. 2 only), or after participants had been allocated
      to a no-training control group. Training that had shown to be effective
      for reducing dual-task interference in response selection was also found
      to be effective for reducing interference in sensory consolidation. In
      addition, we found some evidence that training benefits transferred to the
      sensory consolidation of untrained stimuli. Collectively, these findings
      show that training benefits can transfer across cognitive operations that
      draw on the central bottleneck in information processing. These findings
      have implications for theories of the AB and for the design of
      cognitive-training regimens that aim to produce transferable training
      benefits.
