      arbitrate between the systems when they disagree. Here, we consider
      dual-action choice systems from a normative perspective, using the
      computational theory of reinforcement learning. We identify a key
      trade-off pitting computational simplicity against the flexible and
      statistically efficient use of experience. The trade-off is realized in a
