      the midbrain is thought to cause the rapid prioritization of
      reward-associated visual stimuli. However, existing evidence for this
      incentive salience hypothesis in vision is equivocal, particularly in
      naturalistic circumstances, and little is known about underlying neural
      systems. Here we use human fMRI to test whether reward primes perceptual
      encoding of naturalistic visual stimuli and to identify the neural
      mechanisms underlying this function. Participants detected a cued object
      category in briefly presented images of city- and landscapes. Using
