      goal of this study was to determine whether the advanced preparation of
      simple actions reflected the expected value of the potential outcomes.
      Human subjects were required to direct a saccadic eye movement to a visual
      target that was presented either to the left or right of a central
      fixation point on each trial. Expected value was manipulated by adjusting
      the probability of presenting each target and their associated magnitude
      of monetary reward across 15 blocks of trials. We found that saccadic
      reaction times (SRTs) were negatively correlated to the relative expected
