AB  - The ability to select between possible responses to a given situation is
      central to human cognition. The goal of this study was to distinguish
      between brain areas representing candidate responses and areas selecting
      between competing response alternatives. Event-related fMRI data were
      acquired while 10 healthy adults performed a task used to examine response
      competition: the Eriksen flanker task. Left parietal cortex was activated
      by either of two manipulations that increased the need to maintain a
      representation of possible responses. In contrast, lateral prefrontal and
      rostral anterior cingulate cortices were specifically engaged by the need
      to select among competing response alternatives. These findings support
      the idea that parietal cortex is involved in activating possible responses
      on the basis of learned stimulus-response associations, and that
      prefrontal cortex is recruited when there is a need to select between
      competing responses.
