AB  - It is difficult to perform two tasks at the same time. Such performance
      limitations are exemplified by the psychological refractory period (PRP):
      when participants make distinct motor responses to two stimuli presented
      in rapid succession, the response to the second stimulus is increasingly
      slowed as the time interval between the two stimuli is decreased. This
      impairment is thought to reflect a central limitation in selecting the
      appropriate response to each stimulus, but not in perceptually encoding
      the stimuli. In the present study, it was sought to determine which brain
      regions are specifically involved in response selection under dual-task
      conditions by contrasting fMRI brain activity measured from a response
      selection manipulation that increased dual-task costs, with brain activity
      measured from an equally demanding manipulation that affected perceptual
      visibility. While a number of parieto-frontal areas involved in response
      selection were activated by both dual-task manipulations, the dorsal
      pre-motor cortex, and to a lesser extent the inferior frontal cortex, were
      specifically engaged by the response selection manipulation. These results
      suggest that the pre-motor cortex is an important neural locus of response
      selection limitation under dual-task situations.
