      replaced by new routines. To examine the neural basis of these
      characteristics, we recorded spike activity in cortical and striatal habit
      sites as rats learned maze tasks. Overtraining induced a shift from
      purposeful to habitual behavior. This shift coincided with the activation
      of neuronal ensembles in the infralimbic neocortex and the sensorimotor
      striatum, which became engaged simultaneously but developed changes in
      spike activity with distinct time courses and stability. The striatum
      rapidly acquired an action-bracketing activity pattern insensitive to
      reward devaluation but sensitive to running automaticity. A similar
